text: For those asking why show a Christmas movie trailer in August: Thanksgiving is celebrated in at least 9 different countries between September & November. I know in the US, it is in November & begins the ‚ÄúHoliday season ‚Äú that includes Thanksgiving, Christmas & New Year‚Äôs Day. And consider how fast this year has flown by. It‚Äôll be November/December before we know it.  Also, please stop complaining that the trailer was too long & gave away too much of the film. So what?! Don‚Äôt go see it if you don‚Äôt want to. Many of us have been waiting anxiously for this film & WILL HAPPILY go see it upon its release. Love Emilia & ESPECIALLY the music of George Michael. He approved of this movie before he passed ON CHRISTMAS DAY 2016. It also will feature one of his unreleased songs I hear, in the closing credits. For GM fans, this is a beautiful thing. Despite any & all theories on how this movie will play out or end, I‚Äôll go see it, buy it on dvd when it‚Äôs out & watch it every Christmas. Because it looks amazingly good. And calling it a Lifetime or Hallmark channel movie?! Please.  P.S: the song ‚ÄúLast Christmas ‚Äú never made it to #1 on the charts. You know why? Because that same year, George participated in the charitable song Band Aid‚Äôs ‚ÄúDo they know it‚Äôs Christmas ‚Äú for starving children in Africa. He encouraged his Wham! fans to get THAT song to #1 instead as it was for charity. Last Christmas came in at #2. Later, he had all proceeds from the ‚ÄúLast Christmas ‚Äú single donated to charity forever. I‚Äôm hoping (in honor of George & his kindness) this movie will help the song to reach #1 finally 35 years later. Perhaps Sony will release a new single of Last Christmas along with the unreleased song that‚Äôll be in this movie on the B side? This Christmas will be exactly 3 years since he‚Äôs passed. How fitting. Love you forever George.

text: You know, it's really sad  that people are constantly trying to guess the ending. I for one don't want to know or didn't want to know because I wanted to thoroughly enjoy the movie and it's evolution of it. Sometimes people spoil the ending or put something in your head which makes you not want to go see it. There's been negative press and there's been positive press, so if you're thinking you're going to go see an Academy Award winning film you're in for disappointment. If you just want to go and enjoy the acting, enjoy the cheesiness of this film and most importantly enjoy the music then you're going to walk away and feel happy that you were entertained. I thought it was borderline very good to great. It's just meant for a sweet bit of entertainment and nothing more. That said, whatever you do don't let negative press affect you.  Go and see it for yourself and make your own judgment. I never let outside voices influence most especially movie critics) because my opinion is the one that counts for me.

Finding his phone in the cupboard, Kate realizes that Tom was the organ donor whose heart is now inside her, and that all their interactions were just herself, and she only imagined Tom was there. Going to a small garden which was Tom's favorite place, Kate encounters him again where he says his heart will always belong to her.

text: Honestly I'm very very grateful for this movie having been made. Firstly, the SOUNDTRACK. George Michael and Andrew Ridgeley were overdue for a complete soundtrack of their works, and even if it is dominated by George's back catalogue, Andrew played a big (and small cameo) part in bringing Last Christmas to us. Then there's Emma Thompson's screenwriting which really sparkles with her wit and intelligence, and Emilia Clarke is the perfect vehicle for it to play out on screen. She is completely genuine in this role, and all the more touching because of it. It's also just a lovely advertisement for the beauty and wonder and magic that is London, especially at night. You will NEVER have enough time to discover all of the treasures that London has in store for you.  Such a feel-good Christmas flick that rewards repeated viewings.
